2026-06-25 | Count Subarrays Where Target Is the Majority Element

	Question
Return the number of subarrays in which target is the majority element.
	Approach
1.	Convert the array:
			target → +1
			others → -1.
2.	Compute prefix sums.
3.	A subarray (l...r) has positive sum if:
			prefix[r+1] > prefix[l]
4.	For each prefix sum, count how many previous prefix sums are smaller.
5.	Use a Fenwick Tree (Binary Indexed Tree) to maintain frequencies of prefix sums.
6.	Since prefix sums can be negative, shift them by an offset before using them as indices.
	Time Complexity
	O(n log n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    struct Fenwick {
        vector<int> bit;
        Fenwick(int n) : bit(n + 1, 0) {}
        void update(int idx, int val) {
            while (idx < bit.size()) {
                bit[idx] += val;
                idx += idx & -idx;
            }
        }
        int query(int idx) {
            int sum = 0;
            while (idx > 0) {
                sum += bit[idx];
                idx -= idx & -idx;
            }
            return sum;
        }
    };
    long long countSubarrays(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int offset = n + 2;
        Fenwick ft(2 * n + 5);
        long long ans = 0;
        int pref = 0;
        ft.update(offset, 1); // prefix sum = 0
        for (int x : nums) {
            pref += (x == target ? 1 : -1);
            ans += ft.query(pref + offset - 1);
            ft.update(pref + offset, 1);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
By converting the target to **+1** and every other element to **-1**, the condition
			target appears more than half the time
becomes
			subarray sum > 0.
So the task reduces to counting pairs of prefix sums where the later prefix sum is greater than the earlier one, which can be done efficiently using a Fenwick Tree in **O(n log n)**.
